      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>32 threads, <a href=journal.html?user=631&start=0>1</a> <a href=journal.html?user=631&start=25>2</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;<a href=journal.html?user=631&start=25>Next Page</a></td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101804661375531></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101804661375531><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101804661375531>Lizzard Shadowknight...continues</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101804661375531#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>95 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Apr 5th 5:48 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>This is not the most exciting story I have written to date, but I promise the next installment will be more interesting.&nbsp;&nbsp;As always, please comment either pro or con.  I enjoy the feedback and actually appriciate the constructive critism type.<br><br>Part 20.<br><br>As the sun rose over the plains of The Overthere, I cursed at myself for being caught sleeping and quickly reached for my weapon while trying to locate the person behind the voice.  It was not hard to find the source.  Standing in front of me, with her hand on her hips and a terse frown, stood another Iksar.  &quot;Such language, broodling.  But from the look of you, I would say that you have had a difficult evening.&quot;  <br><br>Eventually, I managed to stand.  Pieces of mud and grass fell off my armor onto the ground as I straightened up.  &quot;My apologies if I have offended.  I was surprised to met anyone out in these wilds.&quot;  My sword moved ever so slightly to the ready.<br><br>The other Iksar's eyes did not miss the movement.  The frown turned into a slight smile.  &quot;You have nothing to fear from me, honorable knight, unless you fear a meal and chance to rid yourself of the mud you collected from the waterhole, yesterday.&quot;   I frowned at the reminder of the previous day's activities but bowed my head in thanks and followed the other Iksar to her camp.  She asked me the story behind my muddy appearance as we walked and I told her the story of my race with the Sarnaks.  &quot;You are lucky.  The knights of the Sarnaks are powerful in their own right.  I am surprised you did not end up as a trophy in their fort.&quot;<br><br>I nodded my head in agreement.  &quot;I was taught to not take any foe lightly.  I will not misjudge the resourcefulness of the Sarnaks again.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Aye, Knight.  That is a good plan, if you wish to continue to breath.&quot;<br><br>We continued our trek.  &quot;I have not introduced myself.  I am...&quot;<br><br>Waving a hand in the air, &quot;You are Shrikke, Shadowknight of Fear, fleeing from the wrath of the cursed Necromancers.  On your way to Velious, if I have heard correctly.&quot;  I opened my mouth to respond, but she continued.  &quot;I was told to look out for you by a mutual friend.  I, by the way, am Klok G'Rshai.  I handle all Iksar commerce in the Overthere, with the Haggle Baron's blessing.&quot;  She stopped and turned to look at me.  &quot;And I am at anyone's service who has enough coin to buy my wares or working toward the good of the Empire.&quot;  She turned back around and continued to walk. <br><br>We continued on for a while and soon came to the edge of the ocean.  Upon the shore was her campsite.  A large tent and a well-used fire pit showed that this had been Klok G'Rshai's home for quite a while.   She started preparing food while I jumped into the ocean with my armor still on to wash away the previous day's adventure.  As I came out of the waves, clean and refreshed, the smell of warm food filled my lungs as I walked back to the camp.  I sat down, grabbed a rag and started wiping down my armor.<br><br>G'Rshai handed me a bowl of steaming broth and sat down across the fire from me.  I thanked her with a nod of my head.  &quot;You don't talk much, knight.&quot; <br><br> It was my turn to smile.  &quot;I have been thinking on a few questions, good Klok.&quot;<br><br>&quot;What questions are those?&quot;<br><br>&quot;First, to whom do you sell your wares?  There are only Dark Elves and Sarnaks in this part of the Kunark.  You must not do much business unless you have an agreement with them and of course, the Haggle Baron would only have you out here if you could turn a profit.&quot;<br><br>&quot;You know the Haggle Baron well, I think,&quot; she replied.  &quot;Continue, please.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Second, you do not have a lot of supplies laying around and the tent is large, but not large enough to store a great amount of inventory.  You must deal in items that are less substantial than food and water.  I am I correct?&quot;<br><br>&quot;Yes, that is a good assessment for the most part.  Information is truly my main commodity.  The Haggle Baron is not interested in politics unless it interferes with profit.  So, I sell the information I can to whoever has the coin to spend.  The Sarnaks and the Dark Elves, Trolls and Ogres all know that I am a reliable resource and allow me to continue to do business as I see fit.&quot;<br><br>Nodding my head, &quot;I understand.&quot;<br><br>The rest of the meal continued in silence.  Afterwards, I cleaned my bowl and started to re-pack my equipment.  I soon noticed my backpack was missing.  I quickly scanned the camp and was about to become concerned when G'Rshai came out of her tent holding a strange looking bag.  &quot;You are looking for your things?&quot; she stated.  &quot;I have packed them in this.&quot;  I took the bag from her and noticed that it was much lighter than I would have expected.  Upon closer inspection, I could tell the material it was made of was magical in nature.  &quot;It is a bag made of the skins of the Evil Eyes that reside in the bowels of the Froglok stronghold.  It floats as the Eyes themselves float, making caring the bag much easier than a normal backpack.&quot;<br><br>I bowed, &quot;This is very generous.&quot;<br><br>&quot;It is nothing.  The Dark Elf who traded it to me was starving.  I made a good profit from him.&quot;  I put on the rest of my armor and thanked the Klok for her help.  &quot;You are welcome, Shrikke.  Before you leave, could I ask you a couple of questions?&quot;<br><br>&quot;I will answer if I can.&quot;<br><br>&quot;You have seen the Vampire in the Tower of Necromancy?&quot;<br><br>I stiffed slightly wondering where this was going.  &quot;Yes, I have seen him.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Can you describe him?&quot;<br><br>&quot;I could, but it would be from my own perspective and I doubt you would be able to deduct who he was before death.&quot;  I strapped my sword to my side, &quot;However, I could give you a name if you like.&quot;<br><br>Her breath caught, &quot;You know his name?  How?&quot;<br><br>I smiled, &quot;Because I was there when he failed the Test.  His name is Hapzass.  He was taken from the Test at the time of his death but I know not how.&quot;  Finishing the last buckle on my sheath.  &quot;Now you know his name as well.&quot;  I looked up and the Klok was not smiling.  &quot;I hope it does you some good.&quot;<br><br>&quot;It is more than I had hoped.&quot;  She sat down on the log next to the fire.  &quot;Now I have some information for you.  You will need to get on the Bloated Belly at the docks of the outpost to leave this place.  The guards around the dock are a combination of dark elves and undead.  It will be difficult to board the ship without one or the other group seeing you.  However, not long ago, two dark elves passed this way.  One was a knight like you, the other a thief bound in the chains of a slave.  She was to be taken back to her homeland for some crime and did not seem pleased about the prospect of returning.  She might be made to help you board the boat, if you could...persuade...the other dark elf to release her.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Which way did they go?&quot;  The Klok pointed in the direction of the outpost.   &quot;My thanks.  I will see you again, I hope.&quot;  I turned and started running to the outpost.<br><br><br>Good hunting all.<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Apr  5 17:47:39 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
