<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101736423924513></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101736423924513><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101736423924513>I have to keep saying sorry...Shrikke Continues</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101736423924513#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>95 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Mar 28th 8:14 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.36]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>February and March where tough.&nbsp;&nbsp;I think I have finally caught up on real life to dedicate a bit more energy to the story of our growing Shadowknight.  I hope that you enjoy this next installment and as always, please don't be afraid to post comment and suggestions.  Good hunting all in the land of Norrath.<br><br>Part 19.<br> <br>As I moved out through the trees, into the pass that leads to the place know as The Overthere, my eyes and thoughts were drawn to the statue of the Iksar warrior that guards the entrance to Warslilks Woods.  It had been built at the height of our power, when the Iksars knew no enemies, only slaves.  We had ruled Kunark then with steel, claw, magic and, most importantly, order.  <br><br>Does that surprise you, the fact that order was so much a part of our society?   Of course it does.  You have listened to the stories told by others who fear us, stories that tell of my people as savage heartless creatures with no thought except destroy and enslave those around us.  Those stories misrepresent the true intent of the Iksar Empire.  Do you think that a society that was simply bent on destruction and chaos could have so completely civilized a continent?  Look at the structures that dot the landscape throughout Kunark.  Look at the roads and the waterways that tie the whole of Kunark together. Not since the Combine Empire has there been such building and architecture.  Are these the works of a people who yearned for death or for simply a better life?  Of course we enslaved the giants, goblins and the other lesser races that infested our Empire.  How could we leave these disruptive and violent creatures free, when they endangered not only themselves but also the Empire with their chaotic behavior?  Instead we used their strength and added it to our own.  Kunark was safe, clean, and orderly while we ruled.  However, we have fallen far as a people since that time.  Now the continent is in ruin and dangerous and falling victim to the forces of chaos, specifically to the elves that have invaded our shores.  Dark Elves, High Elves...it matter not to the Iksar.  Both are agents of chaos.  Dark Elves with their need to glory in death, pain and debauchery make no plans for the future except those that gratify their most basic needs, irrespective of the consequences to themselves or those in their own society.  In contrast, the High Elves have a preoccupation with allowing all beings to follow a  &quot;natural&quot; path in the name of allowing freedom.  Both paths lack purpose.  Both paths lack discipline.  Both paths eventually lead to death and chaos.   Someday, we will burn both their outposts to the ground and show them the errors of their paths.<br><br>When would that time come?  When would my race regain respect?  &quot;Questions for another time,&quot; I thought, as I stepped off the hill and made my way into the rolling, grassy plains of The Overthere.<br><br>The sun was setting as I started this part of my journey and I knew that I would need a place to rest for the night.  As the night truly began, I picked the base of a large boulder to set up camp.  I did not build a fire.  Sarnaks and the Dark Elves roamed the plains, and I did not want to give them something to investigate.  That night I was awoken by the sound of shuffling around my camp.  As I lay on the ground, I peered into the darkness, hoping to see some evidence of what was moving in the night.  And although I could hear and smell something out around my camp, yet I could see nothing.   Thinking that maybe a dark elf or other enemy had cast a spell of invisibility and was moving in to ambush me, I leaped up from my prone position and brought my sword to the ready.  The Dark Reaver, removed from its sheath began to cast an eerie glow over the area.  To my surprise, it was not an enemy or some sort of creature that had awoken me, but a plant.  I had heard of the plants in The Overthere that walked, but I had only half believed the story until this moment.   If the tales I had heard where true, the plants where dangerous only if attacked directly and tended to ignore just about everything else.  Why then, did this plant suddenly stop and turn towards me as I held my sword at the ready?  With my sword still on guard, I moved towards the creature and inspected the sharp thorns that covered its surface and still the creature did not move.  As I moved away back to the base of the rock, I could hear another plant heading directly towards my camp.  It soon joined the first in a silent watch over me.  The two plants did not move and after a while I figured it was safe enough to sleep.  I sheathed my sword and as darkness rushed into the area, I could hear the plants start shuffling away.  &quot;Why would they leave now?&quot; I wondered.  It struck me as I placed my hand on my sword.   I pulled out the burnt out lightstone that still hung around my next and held it over my head.   I brought power to the stone and a white clear light covered the area around my camp.  I could see the plants reverse their movement and come back to my camp.  &quot;They seek light,&quot; I thought.  I was amused by the behavior of these plants.  What series of events had the hated Shissar enacted to give these plants the drive to seek out light?  Within a short time, I had drawn more than twenty of the creatures to my camp, all of them standing dutifully in the light of the stone.  I soon grew bored and knew that the light would eventually draw more then these very odd plants.  I released the power to the stone and heard the plants begin to wander out onto the plains. <br><br>It was lucky, for one of the plants performed an invaluable service to me by shuffling over a large prone object in the grass and inflicted enough damage to make it yelp.  The sarnak knowing that it had given itself away, leapt to its feet and dodging the mobile plants rushed to attack me.  It was not fast enough.  I cast a spell of fear upon the charging beast and smiled as the look of excitement upon the sarnak&amp;#8217;s face changed to a look of terror.  As the beast tried to flee through the plants, it must have stuck one hard enough to anger it.  The plant instantly began whiping the sarnak with those deadly thorns.  I sat back on my rock and watched as the plant struck the fleeing beast over and over again.  With another spell, I cast a curtain of darkness and slowed the sarnak down to allow the plant plenty of opportunity to deal with this creature that had tried to ambush me.  Eventually, the sarnak worked through the terror of the fear spell and started battling the plant, but it was soon over.  The last thing the sarnak felt was me tapping its life force, then death.<br><br>Although this battle was an easy victory, I knew that I needed to leave the area quickly.  This was a young sarnak, recruited recently by its elders to the ways of battle.  One of those elders would be missing this one soon enough.  I looted the body of a few coins, gathered my pack and headed away from the stone as quickly as I could.  I walked through most of the night and eventually stopped under a lone tree on a side of a hill to sit and rest.  As the sun rose on a sleepless night, I could see in the distance running my direction a group of sarnaks.  Thinking these were foolish creatures, I cast a spell and stepped into the shadows of the plains and moved a ways away from the tree.  I would wait until they passed by and simply head in a different direction.  I knew I was in trouble when the largest of the sarnaks got to the tree I had been sitting under and sniffed around its base like a scale wolf, then pointed in my direction.<br><br>I began to run.<br><br>Staying invisible, I made my way over rocks and hills, hoping that the creatures would lose my trail.  It was by the luck of the gods that I came to the shallow, muddy pond.  I quickly ran through the watering hole and out the other side, making sure that a trail went into the high grass on the other side.  I then, carefully, retraced my steps back to the pond and allowed myself to sink into the mud at the bottom.  It was not long before I heard the sound of running sarnak feet as they ran past the pond and back into the plains.  Persistence seems to be a sarnak virtue for they came back to the pond several times that day, to try to pick up the trail.  None of them entered the mud hole except to drink.  So, it seems I spent the second day in the plains of Overthere in a mud hole only coming up for air as needed, then sinking back out of sight.<br><br>It was very dark and I had not seen any sign of the sarnaks for quite a while before I came out of that hole.  I was cold and muddy as I dragged myself and my backpack out of the slime of the pond.  Again, I could not light a fire, so I huddled against another stone and listened to the sounds of the night.  I must have finally dosed off to sleep, because I was surprised by the voice that spoke perfect Iksar.  &quot;Wake up, Knight of Shadow...your day has just begun, I think.&quot;<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Mar 29 10:46:12 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
