<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101508992533947></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101508992533947><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101508992533947>RE: Real Life Rant</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101508992533947#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93468><span id=Guru>tochail the Silent</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>231 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Mar 2nd 12:26 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>/ooc on<br><br>Sorry to hear this happen to you, but I know of many who have similar stories.&nbsp;&nbsp;I suppose that inspectors have to feel useful sometime, though I am surprised that your mom didn't document the request to redo the roof in the first place.<br><br>When my own father had his house built, one of the county inspectors also ordered that he rewire one portion of the living room (for no reason the contractor could determine), so my father asked for a written statement explaining the necessity of the rewire.  Surprisingly (or maybe not), the inspector &quot;got back&quot; to my father several days later and said that the original wiring of the wall was up to code.<br>&nbsp;<br>Icewind Novastorm<br>Koada Dal Cleric of Tunare<br>&lt;&lt;Mith Marr&gt;&gt;</td></tr>
