<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101198720825756></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101198720825756><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101198720825756>Sorry about the slow posts - Shrikke again</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101198720825756#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>95 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Jan 25th 3:34 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I've had this story in my head for a bit, but haven't had time to finish it.&nbsp;&nbsp;I hope you enjoy it.  <br><br>Just to let those of you that read this journal into my RL a little bit, I am a father of two children under 3 years old, and both of them have been sick for bit.  Nothing serious, but they both have not let my wife and I sleep very much over the last couple of weeks.  So, if the story is not up to snuff, I beg your indulance :-)<br><br>As always...please comment or offer suggestion.<br><br>Part 18.<br><br>Most races, if they where honest with themselves, would agree with the statement that death is something to be feared.  However, I have found the soft skinned races truly don't fear death.  They fear the pain just before death.  The feel of a blade sliding between one's ribs or agony of a spell ending a life in a mass of fire, blood and pain, this is what most people actually fear.   What happens after death, in my experience, doesn't concern most.  Everyone understands that the body goes back into the cycle and one's essences become part of whichever god one has followed through the course of life.  This seems on the surface like a reasonable and somewhat pleasurable ending, to bask in the power and knowledge of the gods.  However, this system terrifies me.  It is not that I fear joining my lord, Cazic Thule, or fear becoming part of his will, but that I will cease to have a will of my own.  I fear that once I have died, I will never again personally affect the world.  All chances for personal improvement, power, fame and greatness will be engulfed in the overpowering presence of my god.  Because of this ending to life, I take my life seriously.  I do not spend my time in idle amusements or frivolous vices.   Let those around me play and love and waste their days.<br><br>Death comes to all, but it will not find me wishing I had not reached my potential.<br><br>I walked out of the Field of Bones into Warslilks Woods just before the sun had dropped below the horizon.  It was hard to leave my home behind.  Hard to leave my people at a time when I knew they were in danger of being overcome but the mad plans of the necromancers.  I also still felt the lost of Squire Mharkas.  She was not only the one who showed me my path, but was also the only link to by past that I knew about.  I had not had an opportunity to ask her about my parents before her execution.  I had plenty of opportunity, but never took the time.  I smiled as I saw her in my mind's eye explaining this final lesson,   &quot;Broodling, don't fail to focus on your real priorities, and certainly don't procrastinate in the implementation of those priorities.   Some opportunities only happen once in a lifetime.  Miss them and they will be your undoing.&quot;  Well, I would take this last lesson given to me by the Squire and focus on my ultimate goal:  To come back to Cabilis and bring down the power of the Brood of Kotiz.  They had held the reins of the Empire for too long and had ceased to put their own welfare above the welfare of the people.  And now, they had thrown our lot in with the Vampires.  The undead that walk the Castle of Karnor should have been enough of warning of what could happen when dealing with those who do not have life, but still live.<br><br>These images ran through my mind as I walked the shady under growth of Warslilks Woods.  However, the image of Master Xydoz slowly sliding down an impalement pole was interrupted by an all too familiar sound of breaking limbs and upturned bushes coming towards me   I came to a halt and watched as the Brute walked past me.  I could tell the beast was aware of my presents, as its sulking eyes never left mine as he traveled past.   The Brutes, although strong and violent if provoked, were not dangerous if they were simply left alone to pursue their own paths.  As he disappeared into the undergrowth, I turned to gaze at the path of broken foliage left in the wake of the beast.  Maybe I didn't hear the goblin approach because of the Brute or maybe because of my own pre-occupation with future events, but on the path of fallen limbs stood a large armored goblin.  Now, a single goblin is of no consequence.  I could, even then, destroy all except the strongest goblins that roamed these woods.  However, goblins have a habit of traveling in groups and a seemingly easy encounter could suddenly turn into a mad dash through the undergrowth with a tribe of goblins nipping on your heels.<br><br>The goblin, known, as a battlemaster among it own kind, moved swiftly towards me, arms swinging wildly.  With my sword at the ready, I cast a spell of darkness to slow and hurt the charging fiend.  Unfortunately, I did not have the time I needed to complete the spell before he slammed into me and disrupted my concentration and my spell.  Rocking on my heals and swearing at myself for not judging the goblin's speed better, I was forced to take a couple of glancing, and yet painful, blows to my armor before I could disengage myself from the flaying beast.  I managed to dodge an overhand swing and put enough distance between the battlemaster and myself to bring the Dark Reaver to bear.  I swung the weapon, simply to give myself a moment to regroup, when the Dark Reaver's true power became evident.  I barely scratched the goblin, merely broke the skin of the battlemaster, when suddenly I felt a rush of power.  The sword had absorbed the strength of the goblin and had given it to me.  The goblins features suddenly changed from excitement to fear.  I quickly brought the sword back around to finish the creature, but hit nothing but air.  The goblin had run and was quickly making its way through the woods.  I gave chase, knowing it would bring friends...many friends...to track me down, making my movement through these woods almost impossible. <br><br>There is a certain excitement about knowing that you have a foe running for its very existence, a specific thrill about making an enemy relies that it can do nothing to defeat you and chose to run for his life.  Do not confuse this emotion with the bloodlust of the Dark Elves or the brutal gratification that trolls and ogres find when they reduce another to a pool of matted hair and blood.  An Iksar doesn't find satisfaction in the simple death of other creatures, but the removal of obstacles that stand between them and their goals.  If that obstacle happens to be the death of an enemy or the destruction of a city or the acquisition of a powerful magic item after a long search, the satisfaction is the same.<br><br>I had almost caught the fleeing goblin when the spells hit me.  First, a blast of ice struck my side, throwing me off my feet.  In spite of the numbing pain, I tumbled with the force of the blast and came back up on my feet facing this new threat.   I viewed not one but two new creatures, both goblin magic users.  The second goblin caster was just completeing a spell and I suddenly felt myself tire and sag under the feeling that I should give up this fight, that sleep would be a better course of action.  I fought the sensation and slowly raised my weapon to defend myself, when the fleeing battlemaster returned to the fight.  I dodged the battlemaster's blows while taking damage from the two goblin casters.  I was going to lose this fight.  I had but one option, a spell that I had very recently bought but had little skill in performing.  I swung my sword in a broad arc making the battlemaster retreat far enough give me the opportunity to cast a spell of my own.  As I struggled with the incantation, another spell of ice stuck me and the battlemaster rushed in an attempt to interrupt my thoughts.  It would have looked to anyone watching that the goblins had succeeded in defeating me as I fell lifeless to the ground.   The goblins shrieked in their excitement and rushed my fallen body, quickly binding my hands and feet together.  Two of them threw me on their shoulders as the other reached down to pick up my fallen weapon.  I still smile at the memory of the screams and the blacken fingers that resulted from the goblin picking up the sword of a Shadowknight.  The goblin threw the weapon to the ground cursing and nursing his hand.  His two companions laughed and pointed at the ensuing wounds, almost dropping me off their shoulders.  The incident, I can only imagine, was brought up continuously as we made our way back to the goblin camp, as randomly the damaged goblin would suddenly start howling and screaming at whatever comments where passing between the three of them.  Unfortunately, I only know three words in goblin.  Two of the words are curses; the third is the word for food.  I hadn't heard the third word yet, but even in this pseudo state of death, knew I was in real danger of becoming an entree.  <br><br>Despite the bumpy ride, my Iksar regenerative powers had nearly brought be back to full health by time the group had reached the goblin camp.  Ten or fifteen goblins ran out to meet the small hunting party, all of them screaming and howling at the group who had defeated a lone Iksar.  My body was thrown next to a hut as the goblins that had defeated me started to tell the story of their battle.  For some odd reason, the story took much longer than the actual battle and I doubt the accuracy of the tail they told.  However, I figured the story was almost completed when one of them pointed at the hand of other and the group that had gathered laughed as one and started yelling at the unfortunate goblin that had touched my weapon.  The laugher stopped suddenly as a large goblin stepped out of the hut where my body lay.   I knew this goblin.  He had been the leader the tribe of goblins that inhabited Warslilks Woods for many years, and was desperately wanted dead by the rulers of Cabilis.  He was Grachnist the Destroyer.   And unfortunately, he looked almost happy.   As he stepped out, the other goblins took a half a step back from their leader.   He made a gruff comment to the group that had brought be to camp, then turned and knelt next to my seemingly lifeless corpse.  He took a dagger from his belt and cut the ropes that bound my hand and feet.  He then rolled me on to my back, and lifted one of my arms so he could examine my hand.   It was at this point, as I stared blankly into the sky, I thought my eyes where deceiving me. The hands of this large goblin resembled my hands, but they were not his hands, they where gloves.  Gloves made out of the scales and claws of Iksars.   I knew not how he had fashioned them, but I knew that if I did not leave soon that I would become very intimate with the process.<br><br>He laughed and dropped my arm.  He motioned for two goblins to grab me and take me into his hut.  The goblins picked me up, took me into his hut, and dropped me on a large bloody stone that sat in the middle of the room.  Then, fortunately, they left the hut and me by myself.  I brought myself out of my feigned death and began casting a spell of transportation.  The spell is useful, but unreliable in the distance it carries you.  I hoped it was far enough this time.  The goblins where alerted by the sound of casting, but not even Grachnist was fast enough to get in into the hut before I stepped through to a different location.  I would have not survived the experience without the help of the goblin screams for I displaced myself fairly close to where a guard was standing, fortunately he was already moving towards camp to see what all the screaming was about.  I calmly cast another spell that I had recently bought, one that allowed me to step into the shadows of Warslilks Woods and disappear from my fate as goblin armor.<br><br>I waited until daybreak to circle back and get my sword.  I would not have thought the goblins capable of subtlety, but as came close to the clearing where I had been overpowered by the goblins, there sleeping in a tree was the goblin battlemaster with the burnt hand.  He had figured I would be back for my sword, but with the coming of the dawn, had fallen asleep in the tree.  I searched the surrounding area for others, but did not find any.  I assume that the goblin figured he could take an unarmed Iksar by himself.  He was a foolish goblin.  Still blending with the shadows, I picked up my sword that was still lying on the ground where it had been left from the night before.  My cloak of shadows disappeared as my hand touched its hilt, but I was not concerned.   I walked quietly to the tree where the goblin slept and with a long swing of my Reaver, cut the branch where the goblins sat.  With a crashing of limbs and a howl, the goblin landed on his back.  I stepped on this throat before he regained his breath and brought my sword to the ready.  He stopped struggling when he saw that I did not instantly strike.  &quot;Goblin, do you know any of my speech&quot; I asked.  He looked at me blankly.  I continued with my language lesson by pointing to myself.  &quot;My name is Shrikke.  Do you understand...Shrikke?&quot;  After a couple of minutes and many repeats of my name, a look of understanding came across the goblins face.  He pointed at me with his dirty chipped claw and repeated my name.  I smiled and nodded my head.  Then with two swings of my sword, I cut off both of his hands.  He wailed in pain as the Dark Reaver not only sliced through his wrists, but also robbed him of his strength.  He was bleeding to death, so I cast a healing spell to stop him from dying.  The spell weaken me slightly, but the lose was unimportant compared to the task I had planned for this particular goblin.  I lifted my foot from his throat and pulled him to his feet.  He stood up, looking at his bloody stumps.  I then repeated my language lesson.  I picked up both of his hands and showed him the lifeless forms.  One, to my slight amusment was still slightly backened.  &quot;Shrikke...tell Grachnist that this was done by Shrikke.  Do you understand?  Shrikke.&quot;  The name of the goblin leader brought a light of recognition to the face of the goblin.  I pushed him away from me and he looked over his shoulder.  I lifted my sword again and the goblin battlemaster got the hint and started to run.  I saw him disappear the forest and smiled.  I quickly recast a spell and stepped back into the shadows of Warslilks.  <br><br>The rest of that week, I hunted within shadows of Warslilks Woods for goblins.  Many of them returned to their camp without their hands and the name of Shrikke on their lips.  I assume that Grachnist will remember my name when I return to finish my collection.<br><br>/ooc For some reason...when I import this from Word, the parenthese and apostropies turn into some other characters.  Anyone know why?<br><br>Good hunting all...see ya in Norrath.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Jan 25 15:09:33 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
