<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101010592769918></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101010592769918><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101010592769918>Shrikke is back...</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=631&mid=101010592769918#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>95 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Jan 3rd 7:58 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Everyone, back up on your chairs...at least those who remember Shrikke :-)&nbsp;&nbsp;Yes, I am back.  The holidays are over and end of year stuff is finally done.  I have started a new series of stories for Shrikke that I hope you enjoy.  As always, please comment if you have any opinions on content or writing style.  I have thick skin...I can take it :-)<br><br>Good hunting all...see ya in Norrath.<br><br>Part 17.<br><br>All was still in the hall of the necromancers as I pulled my Khukri out of the chest of Squire Mharkas and saw the light dim slowly from her eyes.   As I knelt beside her, watching the blood pool around her body, I bowed my head and asked that Cazic-Thule welcome and honor the soul that he was soon to receive.  I understood that I had no choice but to kill the Squire, but unlike some, I was not joyful in the fact that I had witnessed, nay participated, in the downfall of my mentor.  My meditations were interrupted by the voice of Master Xydoz.  You have done an excellent job, Shadowknight.  I was surprised that the Arch Duke sent you to perform the ritual for us.   It has always been that the privilege of executing a traitor has fallen to the guild to which they belong, but is it unusual for the ritual to be performed by someone so...let us say close...to the prisoner. He snapped his hands and motioned for the page to come and remove the body.<br><br>I looked up from my prayer from under my banded helm, into the eyes of the page.  I assume that the look on my face conveyed the fact that if the page touched this body, I would surly kill him.  He suddenly stopped and slowly backed away from where I was knelling.  Quietly, I spoke, &quot;This body is not yours to use as you see fit, Master.  She was a Crusader of the Greenmist and I will take her back to my guild for burial.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Oh, you are wrong, Shadowknight.  She had no guild.  She was a traitor to the empire and a danger to those she taught.&quot;  I closed my eyes as he spoke trying to control my rage. He continued, &quot;She had no edict to teach magic.  Only we, the Brood of Kotiz, have been given the charge, from the time of the Emperor, to teach magic to our people.  She broke that law and deserved this ending.  Now, give us the body to keep as an example to what happens to those who fail to follow the law of our people.&quot;<br><br>&quot;All you say may be true, Master.&quot;  Still knelling beside the body of Squire Mharkas, I sheathed my Khukri and picked the body of my teacher.   I stood and turned toward the Master as I held the body. &quot;Or it may be that the Brood of Kotiz has used the responsibility given to them by the Emperor to gain power for themselves at the expense of their own people.  The Emperor made it your responsibility to teach our people magic, not to hoard it for yourselves only to dispense it at your own choosing.  It was not Squire Mharkas that failed her people, but you and those who would sacrifice the greatness of their own race for personal glory.&quot;<br><br>The Master's face clouded over with rage, &quot;You dare talk to a guardian of the Iksar in such a manner?  You will wish you had died before you came out of your egg, Shadowknight.&quot;  Master Xydoz began to cast a spell.  He was a powerful user of magic.  I would have died had I not had activated the circlet that was on my head and faded from view before he could complete his spell.   The page made a feeble attempt to block the door, but did not really slow my progression as I exited the hall. <br><br>I ran through the Tower of Necromancy with the body of the Squire cradled in my arms looking for an easy exit from the hall of death.  I ran down a set of stairs, only to be met by a group of necromancers and their pets coming the opposite direction.  Most of them passed by where I stood without seeing me.  I thought I was safe until the last figure in the group, a hooded form, suddenly stopped and turned toward me.  A voice I had heard before quietly resonated from under the cloak.  &quot;Shrikke?  It is good to see you again.  You who is responsible for the form I now wear.&quot;  The cloaked figure pulled back his hood.   Standing before me stood the form of Hapzass, the broodling Necromancer Larriz and I had killed in order to join a clutch during the Test.   He was older and taller than when I had last seen him, but the greatest change had come in the paleness of his scales and the two long fangs that protruded from the front of his mouth.  &quot;Last time I saw you, I had failed the Test.  Let see now if you can pass my test, broodling.&quot;  I was unable to think for a moment.  A vampire...an Iksar vampire.  This had not been seen for ages and even then had ended badly.  I ripped myself back to the present.  Hapzass was smiling and moving towards me and I could hear the sounds of others coming back down the stairs.   Again, I knew death was about to fall upon me if I did not move.  I had but one option.   Drawing upon the fear that fuels the soul of a Shadowknight, I unleashed my Touch of Harm upon the rushing vampire.  I lost the shadows that surrounded me as magic ripped through the body of Hapzass.  He screamed as every part of his body felt the wrath of the Shadowknight.  Knowing that the pain would not last and knowing that I would be dead if I did not leave the tower quickly, I rushed to my right, ran down the flight of stairs and hurled the body I carried and myself through the open window at the bottom of the landing.  The fall was long and dark, but I was relieved when I hit the canal and the safety of the water.  Without coming up for air, I swam for East Cabilis dragging the body of the Squire behind me.  No one followed me in the canal, but I knew that I would not be spending any more time in the Tower of Necromancy.  I did not know it until that moment, but I had made a very bad enemy, an enemy with a very long memory.<br><br>I managed to drag the dead body out of the canal and into the temple of the Shadowknights.  Lord Gikzic was waiting for me as I stepped through the teleporter. He didn't say a word, but took the body of Squire Mharkas and laid it upon a table.  He then turned to me, &quot;I am glad you are alive, Shrikke.  Already, we have received a command from the Necromancers that you are to be sent back to the Tower of Necromancy immediately for trial.  I believe the charges say something about heresy and the unprovoked attack upon one of their members.&quot;<br><br>I nodded my head and handed him the Circlet of Shadows he had lent to me, &quot;They are correct in their charges, but not complete in their details, Lord.&quot;  I explained completely what had happened in my time at the tower.  &quot;They wanted to keep the body of the Squire.  I'm sure that they would have used it for the same dark purposes that created the Vampire Hapzass, Lord.  The Necromancers are moving in a direction that endangers us all.  Can we do nothing about it?&quot;<br><br>&quot;Shrikke, go away&quot;  I blinked, twice.  What was he saying to me?  &quot;You are still young and the enemies that you face are beyond you.  I will say that I have not seen you.  I will say that you escaped out of the city before we could send you back to that pit of death.&quot;  He put his hand on my shoulder. &quot;If you want to truly influence the path of your people.  If you truly want to kill those who would destroy you, then go...grow strong in the arts of the Shadowknight.  Then comeback and face these vipers and bring them death.&quot;<br><br>&quot;Where should I go, Lord?  There is no place an Iksar is welcome.  Do I become like the bandits that roam the wilds of Kunark?&quot;<br><br>Lord Gikzic shook his head, &quot;No, Shrikke.  I suggest you go to Velious.  Gain the favor of the giants or dwarves that live on that frozen continent.  There you can learn what you must to help deal with this danger.  If you survive, then come back to Cabilis.  We will be waiting for you, and so with they, I'm afraid.  He opened a chest and pulled out a long dark sword that was familiar to me.  &quot;Do you know this sword, Shadowknight?&quot;<br><br>&quot;Yes, Lord.  It is Squire Mharkas' Dark Reaver,&quot;  I replied.<br><br>&quot;No, broodling.  This is your Dark Reaver.  Now leave.  Before things become more complicated and dangerous.&quot;<br><br>I left the City of Cabilis, through Field of Bones only stopping at the Tower of Kurns to replenish my supply of bone chips.  As I headed  to Warsilks Woods, I stopped and looked upon my city.  I left my city as an outcast.  And someday, I would return to this city of my race, but not as an outcast.  Not as an orphan disowned by his people, but as an angel of death.  <br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Jan  4 12:18:45 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
