<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100440202216575></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100440202216575><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=631&mid=100440202216575>More of Shrikke</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=631&mid=100440202216575#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>95 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 29th 7:33 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Greetings again.&nbsp;&nbsp;I'm sorry I have not posted in a while.  RL and work gets busy and sucks up my EQ time.<br><br>The next installment of Shrikke's Bio.  I need to wrap this up I think or it will become a book unto itself :-)<br><br>Thanks again for praise and encouragement.  Please feel free to comment or suggest.<br><br>Part 10.<br><br>Life without purpose is worthless.  Find a being without purpose and you have found nothing.  Find a purpose without a being and you have found opportunity.  Truly, all other races on Norrath hate the Iksar.  Even the Dark Elves who celebrate death, torture and bloodshed will generally not deal with those of my kind.  There is a reason for this.  The Iksar can be expected to do exactly what will suit the purpose of continued existence for our race without hesitation, emotion or thought of sacrifice.  If that means the death of an innocent or a thousand innocents or entire race, that is acceptable as long as the Iksar advance in power.  However, we do not enjoy such practices in and of themselves.  We do not glorify in the death of another.  Death is a tool.  Fear is a tool.  We use tools to build our future; we do not let the tools dictate that future. <br><br>I do not remember coming to the wilderness from my home with Squire Mharkas.  I do not remember how I got a large bump on my head.  I was told once that often trauma to the head can cause the loss of memory.  I do remember beginning to regain consciousness and my head throbbing when a great river of power flashed through my body.  I was instantly awake and alert.  My eyes opened to an adult Iksar who I had never seen standing over the top of me wearing a blue robe with a mace hanging on his belt.  He said nothing to me, but stood up, turned and walked into the dark forest.  He then began to speak quietly to another I had not seen, standing under the darkness of a tree.   I could not make out their words, so I started looking around trying to judge exactly where I was and what exactly was going to happen.  It was dark just before dawn.  The world around me was a mixture of trees and ebon hues.  The Iksar in blue robes nodded his head and began to walk away into the forest.  He had not taken twenty steps when there was thrum of a longbow from the direction of silhouette behind the tree.  I turned, to see an arrow lodged at the base of the skull of the blue robed Iksar.  He slumped face first onto the forest floor with hardly a sound.  I reacted by backing quickly into the shrubbery behind me hoping that I was not the next target.<br><br>The shadow behind the tree stepped out into the clearing as he concentrated on unstringing his bow.  It was an old Iksar, slightly bent with age.  He finished with his bow and looked around the clearing until his gaze fell upon the shrub where I was desperately trying to become one with the fauna.  &#8220;Come out broodling.  Your death will not come by my hand today.&#8221;<br><br>I slowly made my way out of the bushes, my gaze never leaving the old lizard.  &#8220;Why did you have to kill that one?&#8221; indicating the dead Iksar.<br><br>&#8220;It is the rules.  No one may know where the Test is conducted, except for myself and the leaders of each of the major guilds.  Any who happen upon this place by accident must be killed.  And any who are sent here on purpose are meant to be tested.  That one failed.&#8221;  The old Iksar pointed toward the bundle prepared for me by Squire Mharkas.  &#8220;Take your pack.  And keep up, the camp is a short ways away.&#8221;<br><br>I grabbed my bag and turned to see the old one already making progress through the dark undergrowth.  I would have to hurry to catch up, not having any idea where this place was located, or how to find my way back to my home if I got lost but I needed something from the dead Iksar.  I sprinted over to the body and grabbed the mace that still hung from the Iksars&#8217; belt.  I could not see it going to waste here in the forest.  With the mace in one hand and my bundle over my shoulder I ran to catch the old one.  For a moment I thought he had lost me.  In time, I spotted him ahead and managed to keep him in sight until I finally caught up with him.  He did not say anything about the mace although I am sure he knew from where I had gotten it.  He moved easily for an ancient one.  Age did not seem to hinder his movements through the woods as I nearly ran to keep up with him.<br><br>The rays of the sun where just beginning to stream over the tops of the mountains, giving the forest a tint of purple, when the old Iksar held his arm straight out to the side as an indication for me to stop.  My question was halted with a motion.  &#8220;Move behind that tree and do not move until I come for you, broodling,&#8221; he whispered.  I quickly made my way behind the tree and looked back the way I had came in time to see the old one with a motion of power gather the shadows of the forest around him and disappear.  He was a Knight of Shadow, like Squire Mharkas.<br><br>I waited quietly behind the tree, holding my newfound mace tightly with both hands, listening to the sounds of the early morning forest.  Each sound I heard making me suspect a hidden threat.   I spent until the sun was clearly above the mountains jumping each time a bird would take wing or rabbit would run for cover.  Eventually, as the morning passed and the old Iksar did not return, I grew tired of jumping and started enjoying the forest scene around me.  With my back to the tree and the warm morning sun shining warmly on my green scales, I started to dose.<br><br>I awoke with a start with a knife pressed up against my throat.  Three Iksars about my own age or a little older stood in front of me, while a fourth held the knife firmly under my chin.   The one holding the knife spoke, &#8220;What clutch are you with, broodling.&#8221;  I hesitated to answer.  I did now know what he was talking about.  Seeing my hesitation, the largest of the three in front of me pulled a dagger from her belt.  &#8220;We do not have time for dealing with this problem.  Sorry broodling, the Test is over for you.&#8221;  And with that, she lunged forward, trying to sink the knife into my belly for a quick kill.  I moved.  Luckily the one holding the knife to my throat seemed just as surprised at the abrupt attack as I and also jumped away.  Luckily, he managed to miss cutting my throat as I twist around the tree and away from the incoming knife.   Instead of the knife burying itself in my stomach, I felt the blade force itself through my scales and into my flesh along my ribs.  I would have made it behind the tree and hopefully into a full run if not for something getting caught between my feet.  Instead, as I dove around the tree and out of the way, I tripped and fell headlong into ball of arms, legs, and tail.  Cursing and thinking that death was just a few steps behind me, I reached down to remove the object that, even as I tumbled, was hampering my escapes.   My hand fell upon my looted mace.  Hearing the others coming towards me, I grabbed the mace with both hands, got me feet under me, and as I heard one of them coming up behind me, I stood up swinging the mace in a full circle.  I had never killed another being before.  I had seen many slaves and prisoner killed, but had never killed anyone myself.  The mace came into contact with the skull of the closest pursuer.  There was a sound of metal hitting bone and the young Iksar fell to the ground in a mass of blood and scale.  The weight of the mace spun me around even after the blow.   I tried to quickly bring the mace back to face my enemies.  When I did, they stood two arm lengths away from me, holding their own weapons, but they where not looking at me, but behind me.  I cautiously looked over my shoulder to see the old Iksar standing off to the side and behind me.<br>	&#8220;A poor showing, broodlings,&#8221; talking to the three young Iksars.  &#8220;This one should be dead if you had worked together.  However, may I be so bold as to suggest that you consider attacking an enemy instead of the newest member of your clutch?&#8221;  The others dropped the tips of their weapons and started looking at the ground in shame or frustration.  &#8220;Now you are again short two members.  It will be a difficult year, I think.&#8221;  The other three broodlings looked at me, then at the body of their fallen companion.  The old one continued, &#8220;The broodling doesn&#8217;t have a name yet, but considering what just occurred, I think we shall call him Shrikke.&#8221;<br><br>Part 11.<br><br>The Test of Sufficiency is a period between a broodling&#8217;s sixth and eighth season when a broodling is taken out to the wilds of Kunark, placed with a clutch of other young Iksars and left to endure.  Food, water, shelter and safety are in questionable supply during those years.   Young Iksars must learn to not only forage from the forest all they need to survive during the two years, but also be prepared to protect themselves and their clutch from the wandering creatures of the area and the intrusion of other clutches.   <br><br>The Test, from what I could discern, is held in a very large, round valley with only one pass.  The Testmaster, the ancient Iksar who introduced me to my clutch, guards the pass.  His responsibility was to regulate the types and numbers of creatures that entered the valley and to place candidates into clutches when they began the Test.   His greatest challenge seemed to be keeping balance within the valley.  Balance between the creatures of the area and the various clutches camped around the valley.   Too many creatures or creatures possessing too much power would simply overrun the clutches, too few creatures would limit the opportunity for each clutch to work together and be tested effectively.   In all things of the valley, the Testmaster was ultimately responsible.<br><br>How the Test came into existence is unknown to me. I would guess that the guild leaders may have some of the lore concerning the Test, but I have not asked and I doubt they would freely give such information.<br><br>And so, I found myself with three other Iksar broodlings wondering the wilds of Kunark.  It seems that I had &#8220;accidentally&#8221; killed the oldest and strongest of the broodlings and at the same time interrupted a raid that the clutch had planned upon another nearby group.  The broodling I had killed was named Ysshis.  She had wished to become a trooper and train at the Guild of Warriors after the Test.  Instead, the group looted her body, gave me the clothing, and buried it with their own claws so that it would not attract unwanted creatures.  Goblin whelps, I was told, are attracted to the bodies of the dead.   I had never seen a goblin.   I had a feeling that would change in the near future.<br><br>The Testmaster waited until the body was buried to depart. &#8220;I take my leave of you broodlings.  Chasnic&#8230;&#8221; the oldest remaining Iksar in the clutch &#8230;&#8221;inform Shrikke of the rule of the Test, as well as the penalty for breaking the rule. &#8220;  The Testmaster looked at the sun through the trees, then back at us.  &#8220;It is getting late in the afternoon.  I would head back to camp and set defenses for the night, if I where you.  Of course, I am not you.&#8221;  With that he turned and wandered into the forest, moving quickly through the growing shadows.<br><br>Chasnic turned to the three of us as the Testmaster disappeared from sight.  &#8220;I am Chasnic, this is Zzrantan, and he,&#8221; pointing at a small broodling burrowing under a fallen log, &#8220;is Larriz.  There is one rule to the Test.  Don&#8217;t leave the valley or you will be killed.  You may leave the Clutch, you may make your own camp anywhere in the valley, you may do whatever you want, but it you try to leave the valley, death will find you. Any questions?  No? Good then.  We need to get out of here.  Zzrantan, you don&#8217;t think that the Testmaster was giving us a hint of something that could happen tonight?&#8221;<br><br>Zzrantan was a big broodling, nearly a full head taller than myself.  In the sheath at his side he wore the looted dagger that had opened up the gash along my ribs.  The wound was basically healed, but the memory had not faded.  &#8220;I don&#8217;t know&#8230;probably.&#8221;  Zzrantan looked around the forest with a bit of anxiety   &#8220;Goblin crap.  We need to get back to camp if the dead are walking tonight.&#8221;<br><br>Chasnic turned back to me.  &#8220;Get your stuff and give that mace to Zzrantan.  He will make better use of it than you if the dead come to visit tonight.&#8221;<br><br>I hesitated a moment before handing the mace to Zzrantan.  Zzrantan reached out his hand and spoke.  &#8220;I could take it after the dead have made you one of their own?&#8221; <br><br>Understanding the threat, but unwilling to give up my mace.  &#8220;In trade for your extra dagger and sheath.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Of course.&#8221;  Zzrantan untied the dagger and sheath from his waist and tossed them to the ground at my feet, &#8220;Although you will have to clean the dagger.  It has some blood on it, I think.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;I think that you will not find my weapon to be any cleaner.&#8221;  I handed the mace to the larger broodling and picked the dagger and my pack off the ground.<br><br>Chasnic turned to the small broodling digging under the fallen log, &#8220;Larriz, have you found anything to eat?&#8221;<br><br>A dirt covered head popped up over the log.  &#8220;Yep, but only a few grubs and earthworms.  I hope that Shrikke&#8217;s parents where good enough to pack him a meal he can share with the rest of us.&#8221;<br><br>I hadn&#8217;t looked in the pack.  &#8220;I don&#8217;t know,&#8221; shrugging my shoulders.<br><br>&#8220;It doesn&#8217;t matter.&#8221;  Chasnic said.   &#8220;Either you have some and will share with the rest of us or not.  We don&#8217;t have time to look for anymore.   Larriz grab what is there and let&#8217;s go.  I would rather be waiting for the dead, if they come, then be chased by them.&#8221;<br><br>The discussion was over.  As I ran through the woods behind Zzrantan I couldn&#8217;t help but wonder sort of night this would become.  These broodlings believed that the dead would walk the forest tonight.  I wondered about the dead Iksar in the blue robe.  Would he come back to claim his mace.  I almost laughed when I decide that it was not my worry anymore, the mace was in someone else&#8217;s hands.<br><br>We stopped by a small clearing next to a stream.  A small hut of logs and branches sat against a large boulder with a small fire pit in front.  &#8220;That is our home.  And for the next two years it is your home, Shrikke.  That is if the dead don&#8217;t kill us all tonight.&#8221;  I was hoping for some type of sarcasm to follow the statement, some indication that things where not as bad as I thought they were going to be.  Unfortunately, it did not come.  &#8220;Listen to me and Zzrantan.  Do what we ask, quickly.  And watch everyone&#8217;s back.  Now the first order of business if for us to gather some wood for the fire and find some fist sized rocks.  But first, Shrikke&#8230;see what you have in the pack.  I don&#8217;t feel like eating earthworms tonight.&#8221;<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
