<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100215096165467></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100215096165467><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=631&mid=100215096165467>Shrikke's Bio -  3rd Post</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=631&mid=100215096165467#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=631><span id=Scholar>Sir Parttime</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>95 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Oct 3rd 7:16 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I am humbled by your response to Shrikke's Bio.&nbsp;&nbsp;I just hope these aren't getting too long for everyone to enjoy.  Please feel free to make suggestions and comments.  I have a pretty thick skin.  Good hunting.<br><br>Part 4. <br>  <br>Soon after the death of the halfling slave, my daily routine changed.  Up to that point, I would usually have a day with balanced amounts of eating, sleeping and playing organized by Squire Mharkas or one of slaves.  Added to my routine just before bed, was a time of meditation with Squire Mharkas.  I, like most two year olds had very little experience with sitting in one place for extended periods of time and would often not be meditative for very long.  I would try my best to stay quiet and concentrate on whatever topic the Squire had given to me, usually without much success.  It was odd to me at the time, as stringent as Squire Mharkas was about most of my activities; she was patient in this one.  No matter how often I would ask a question or squirm about on my pillow, she would quietly remind me of the task at hand.<br> <br>It was a number of cycles of the moon before I had any idea of the purpose of this nighttime ritual.  This night, Squire Mharkas told me a tale of a Lord Shadowknight named Dzanthul.  This Lord was given the task of killing a giant that had been plundering the countryside and killing many Iksars.  He had no trouble finding the giant.  The brunt had left a trail of death and carnage that a blind froglok could follow.  When he finally had caught up with the giant, he found a score of Iksars skinned and hung in the trees ready to be eaten.  Enraged by the sight, Dzanthul rushed into clearing to kill the giant.  The Shadowknight did not know that the giant had a helm that made him invisible and did not see the swinging axe the giant wielded.  The blow from behind caught Dzanthul in the ribs underneath the arm, throwing the Knight into a heap on the edge of the clearing.  The blow would have killed the Lord Shadowknight if not for his magical Dreadscale armor.  The giant thinking the Shadow Knight dead, sat down to feast on the skinned Iksars.  Halfway through the meal, the giant heard a moan come from the fallen Knight.  The Knight was regaining consciousness.  The giant cursed himself for not making sure the Shadowknight was dead and picked up a very heavy stone to crush the Lord.  At that moment, Dzanthul regained consciousness and rolled on to his back.  Seeing the giant coming towards him, with the large rock over his head, the Shadowknight quickly cast a spell of Steal Strength upon the giant.  The giant, weakened, was unable to hold on the to rock.  The rock came then crashing down upon the giant&#8217;s head, killing him.  The Lord Shadowknight plundered the body of the giant, taking the helm for his own, and returned to his home as a hero.<br><br>I asked Squire Mharkas if the story was true.  She said that the story was true.  I then asked her how the Lord had cast the spell.  She said that he had practiced for many years to sense the forces around him and that through controlling those forces; he was able to absorb the strength of the giant.  I knew I could ask one more question before Squire Mharkas and I began our nightly exercise.  I asked when was I going to be able to start practicing like the Shadow Knight Lord.  She said that I already had started.  <br><br>Then I understood.<br><br>Part 5.<br><br>I was in my fourth year.  As was the custom, after the morning meal, I would be taken by one of slaves to a courtyard just outside of the Temple to play with other Iksar hatchlings.   Throwing sticks and balls, chasing each other around the courtyard, and swimming in the canals where common activities.  Occasionally, one of the adult Iksars would organize a game of hide and seek.  Little did we know how important that particular game would become to our continued existence.<br><br>I remember a day when the sun shone high in the sky and was hot even before midday.  We asked the supervising Trooper if we could go down to the canals to swim.  Even at four years, an Iksar is at home in the water.  The Trooper said no, without explanation.  This confused our little playgroup.  The sun was hot and the canal was not running swiftly.  Why would he not let us swim?  He was being cruel without cause.  We crowded around the Trooper, asking incessantly for him to allow us swim.  His face grew hard and with a sweep of his pike he pointed towards the canal and told us to swim all we wanted.  <br><br>We all started running to the canal, suddenly a thought occurred to me and I stopped.  I turned toward the trooper, &#8220;What is the reason you do not want us to swim?&#8221;<br><br>He looked at me blankly.  &#8220;Funny that you ask, but as your playmates will find out, this is the time of year when the fish in the canals are breeding.  They will attack anything that jumps into the water. &#8220;  <br><br>Without thanking the trooper, I turned and ran after my friends yelling, trying to warn them about the fish.   They did not hear me.  Most were fortunate and got out of the water before the fish did any real damage.  Two of those playmates, I never saw again.  And one was considered &#8220;lucky&#8221; because the fish did not kill him, but took only an arm.  That hatchling now works in the slave pens, passing out meals and removing the filth. I would like to hear, sometime, his comments about luck.<br><br>The Trooper brought me before Squire Mharkas and told the story. I stood listening to the story with my head hung low.  I was ready for my punishment.  I was not sure why, but I felt as if I had failed my friends and Squire Mharkas.  Failure always has an effect and I was ready to come to terms with that effect.  The Trooper finished the story, bowed to Squire Mharkas and left our rooms.  I looked up, expecting a harsh conclusion to this day, to see the Squire looking pleased.  She must have seen the look of confusion on my face, because she knelt down, so she could talk to me eye to eye.<br><br>&#8220;I would have been angry if you had jumped in the canal with the other hatchlings.  You would have had your life made uncomfortable for many cycles of the moon.  I would have been angrier if you had died today.  So angry, I would have raised your bones and used them as an example to my next student as to what happens to foolish hatchlings that do not think through an event through before acting.   You did think today before you acted.  You asked the correct questions at the correct time.  That is success.  The hatchlings that were lost today are lost because they failed that test.  They were your friends and I&#8217;m sure you feel sorrow, but we Iksar do not have the luxury of surrounding ourselves with fools.  Even if those fools are our friends or our students.  Foolishness only leads to death.&#8221;  She paused and took my hand in hers.  &#8220;You pleased me today and today I will give you a reward for your success. &#8220;  In my hand, I felt her place the cold form of a crystal.<br>	<br>&#8220;What is this,&#8221; I asked, turning my hand over to look at the clear crystal.<br><br>&#8220;This is a lightstone&#8230;a burntout lightstone.  It comes from a creature called a willowwisp.  A normal lightstone shows a clear light.  This one does not have that ability on it&#8217;s own anymore.  However, if a person can concentrate hard enough and bring the correct forces to bear on the stone, it can again shine brightly.  I bought it for you too practice with when we meditate each night.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Thank you, Squire Mharkas,&#8221; taking the stone and placing it in my pocket.<br>	<br>&#8220;One more thing hatchling, do not tell anyone about the crystal. And I do mean anyone, not a slave or another hatchling.  To do so could have effects that neither of us will be able to deal with.  Do you understand?&#8221;<br>	<br>&#8220;I understand, Squire. I will obey.&#8221;<br>&nbsp;<br>Shrikke - Knight of Fear<br>Bristlebane</td></tr>
